PuTTY source code README
========================

This is the README for the source code of PuTTY, a free Windows and
Unix Telnet and SSH client.

PuTTY is built using CMake <https://cmake.org/>. To compile in the
simplest way (on any of Linux, Windows or Mac), the general method is
to run these commands in the source directory:

  cmake .
  cmake --build .

These commands will expect to find a usable compile toolchain on your
path. So if you're building on Windows with MSVC, you'll need to make
sure that the MSVC compiler (cl.exe) is on your path, by running one
of the 'vcvars32.bat' setup scripts provided with the tools. Then the
cmake commands above should work.

To install in the simplest way on Linux or Mac:

  cmake --build . --target install

On Unix, pterm would like to be setuid or setgid, as appropriate, to
permit it to write records of user logins to /var/run/utmp and
/var/log/wtmp. (Of course it will not use this privilege for
anything else, and in particular it will drop all privileges before
starting up complex subsystems like GTK.) The cmake install step
doesn't attempt to add these privileges, so if you want user login
recording to work, you should manually ch{own,grp} and chmod the
pterm binary yourself after installation. If you don't do this,
pterm will still work, but not update the user login databases.

Documentation (in various formats including Windows Help and Unix
`man' pages) is built from the Halibut (`.but') files in the `doc'
subdirectory. If you aren't using one of our source snapshots,
you'll need to do this yourself. Halibut can be found at
<https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/halibut/>.

The PuTTY home web site is

    https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/

If you want to send bug reports or feature requests, please read the
Feedback section of the web site before doing so. Sending one-line
reports saying `it doesn't work' will waste your time as much as
ours.

See the file LICENCE for the licence conditions.


Building on macOS (GUI)
-----------------------

PuTTY is gaining a native macOS GUI built with Swift and AppKit. The
full phased plan is in MACOS_GUI_PLAN.md in the repository root.

Prerequisites
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  - macOS 15 (Sequoia) or later as the deployment target
  - Xcode 16 or later (includes the Swift 6 toolchain and macOS 15 SDK)
  - Xcode Command Line Tools: xcode-select --install
  - Active developer directory pointing at Xcode (not CLT alone), e.g.:
      sudo xcode-select -s /Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer
  - CMake 3.28 or later
  - Ninja (recommended) or the Xcode generator
  - Python 3 (used by the icon generation scripts at build time)

Verify the toolchain before configuring:

  xcode-select -p
  xcrun --find swiftc && swiftc --version
  cmake --version

GUI build vs CLI / GTK build
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

On Darwin, CMake selects the platform according to PUTTY_MACOS_GUI:

  PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=OFF (default)
      Uses the existing unix/ platform. Builds CLI tools (plink, pscp,
      psftp, …) and, if GTK is found, the legacy GTK-based putty and
      pterm binaries. This is unchanged from a normal Unix/macOS build.

  PUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON
      Uses the new macos/ platform. Builds the native AppKit GUI
      (PuTTY.app, and further apps as they are added) plus CLI tools
      linked against the macos/ C platform layer. Does not use GTK.

Use separate build directories for GUI and CLI/GTK builds; do not
reconfigure the same build tree between the two modes.

Typical GUI build commands
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Release build (produces PuTTY.app):

  cmake -B build-macos-gui -G Ninja \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0

  cmake --build build-macos-gui

The application bundle is written to build-macos-gui/PuTTY.app. Run it
directly:

  open build-macos-gui/PuTTY.app

Fast local development build (native architecture only, shorter compile
times):

  cmake -B build-macos-gui-dev -G Ninja \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=OFF \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0

  cmake --build build-macos-gui-dev

Universal 2 (Intel + Apple Silicon) release builds
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Release GUI builds should produce a single Universal 2 .app bundle: one
Mach-O executable containing both arm64 (Apple Silicon) and x86_64
(Intel) slices. Use the Xcode generator (Swift requires it for fat
binaries); PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON is the default:

  cmake -B build-macos-gui -G Xcode \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_GUI=ON \
    -DPUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON \
    -DCMAKE_OSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET=15.0

  cmake --build build-macos-gui --config Release

Ninja builds are supported for fast single-architecture development
(PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=OFF). If PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=ON is set with
Ninja, CMake warns and builds the host architecture only.

Verify that the app executable is Universal 2:

  lipo -info build-macos-gui/Release/PuTTY.app/Contents/MacOS/PuTTY

Or run the CMake verification target after building:

  cmake --build build-macos-gui --config Release --target verify-universal

Expected lipo output includes both x86_64 and arm64, for example:

  Architectures in the fat file: x86_64 arm64

For day-to-day development on one machine, PUTTY_MACOS_UNIVERSAL=OFF
builds only the host architecture and is significantly faster.

CLI-only build on macOS (unchanged)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  cmake -B build-macos-cli -G Ninja
  cmake --build build-macos-cli

See MACOS_GUI_PLAN.md for signing, notarization, and further GUI
targets (pterm.app, PuTTYgen.app) as they are added in later phases.
